No, absolutely not:

   =20

None of this! Come on.=09=E2=80=9CTemporarily on hold=E2=80=9D is not a thi=
ng. Elon Musk has signed a  binding contract requiring him to buy Twitter. =
Legions of bankers and lawyers and Twitter employees and special-purpose-ve=
hicle promoters are working to fulfill his legal obligation to get the deal=
 closed. =E2=80=9CThe parties hereto will use their respective reasonable b=
est efforts to consummate and make effective the transactions contemplated =
by this Agreement,=E2=80=9D says the merger agreement. (Section 6.3(a).) He=
 can=E2=80=99t just put that =E2=80=9Con hold.=E2=80=9D=09That contract doe=
s not allow Musk to walk away if it turns out that =E2=80=9Cspam/fake accou=
nts=E2=80=9D represent more than 5% of Twitter users. We   discussed this l=
ast month, when Twitter admitted in a securities filing that it had (slight=
ly) overestimated its daily active users for years. The merger agreement co=
ntains a provision=C2=A0that allows Musk to walk away if Twitter=E2=80=99s =
securities filings are wrong =E2=80=94=C2=A0and this 5% number is in its se=
curities filings =E2=80=94=C2=A0but only if the inaccuracy would have a =E2=
=80=9CMaterial Adverse Effect=E2=80=9D on the company. (See  Sections 4.6(a=
) and 7.2(b).) That is an incredibly high standard: Delaware courts have  a=
lmost never found an MAE.=C2=A0An MAE has to be something that would =E2=80=
=9Csubstantially threaten the overall earnings potential of the target in a=
 durationally-significant manner,=E2=80=9D the  courts have said;=C2=A0ther=
e is a rule of thumb that an MAE requires a 40% decrease in long-term profi=
tability. If it turned out that 6% or 20% or 50% of Twitter accounts are bo=
ts, that will be embarrassing and might even reduce Twitter=E2=80=99s futur=
e advertising revenue, but will it be an MAE? No.=09=E2=80=9CPending detail=
s supporting calculation=E2=80=9D is not how this works. This disclosure =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cthe average of false or spam accounts ... repr=
esented fewer than 5% of=E2=80=9D Twitter=E2=80=99s=C2=A0monetizable=C2=A0d=
aily active users =E2=80=94=C2=A0has been in Twitter=E2=80=99s  securities =
filings for  many=C2=A0years, always with a caveat that =E2=80=9Cin making =
this determination, we applied significant judgment, so our estimation of f=
alse or spam accounts may not accurately represent the actual number of suc=
h accounts, and the actual number of false or spam accounts could be higher=
 than we have estimated.=E2=80=9D Musk had the opportunity to read these fi=
lings before offering to buy Twitter, and he had the opportunity to do due =
diligence on these numbers before signing the deal. (He declined.) He can=
=E2=80=99t now go to Twitter and say =E2=80=9Cactually now you need to prov=
e that your user numbers are right.=E2=80=9D If he wants to walk, he has to=
 prove that they=E2=80=99re wrong, and also that they=E2=80=99re wrong in a=
 way that has a material adverse effect on the business. Which he obviously=
 can=E2=80=99t do.What is going on here? My initial reaction was that Musk =
was=C2=A0joking, that this was just a way to troll people online. It is, af=
ter all, Friday the 13th. =E2=80=9CStill committed to acquisition,=E2=80=9D=
 he tweeted two hours later.=C2=A0Obviously this would be a bad joke,  inso=
far as it =E2=80=9Csent Twitter stock tumbling as much as 25% in premarket =
trading.=E2=80=9D You are not supposed to say things that aren=E2=80=99t tr=
ue and that will affect the stock of a public company that you are trying t=
o buy. That is what is usually called =E2=80=9Csecurities fraud,=E2=80=9D o=
r what I sometimes like to call =E2=80=9Clite securities fraud.=E2=80=9D Mu=
sk has a long history of lite securities fraud: He used to  make jokes abou=
t Tesla Inc.=C2=A0 introducing new products=C2=A0or  going bankrupt, and he=
 notably  settled a  fraud lawsuit with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission because he  tweeted that he had secured funding to take Tesla priv=
ate but  had not. If he just woke up feeling frisky and tweeted a joke abou=
t Twitter=E2=80=99s bot accounts, a joke that wiped billions of dollars off=
 Twitter=E2=80=99s market capitalization,=C2=A0that would be totally unsurp=
rising. Bad! Not really allowed! But very much in character.Another possibi=
lity is that Musk really is laying the groundwork to walk away from his dea=
l with Twitter. There is a popular view that Musk has the option to abandon=
 the deal if he pays a $1 billion breakup fee. As we have  discussed around=
  here, that  just isn=E2=80=99t true: The contract gives Twitter the right=
 to force him to close, and put up the $27.5 billion of equity[1] that he h=
as committed to the deal, as long as his debt financing is available. (Sect=
ion 9.9(b).)=C2=A0The contract also gives Twitter the right to go to court =
to force him to try to get that debt financing. (Sections 6.10(a) and 9.9(a=
).) There is, so far, no reason to think the debt financing=C2=A0won=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0be available =E2=80=94=C2=A0his banks are large and solvent and h=
ave signed reasonably unconditional commitment letters[2] =E2=80=94=C2=A0an=
d so no reason to think he can get out of the deal.On the other hand, what =
if he does it anyway? What if he just says =E2=80=9Cno, I=E2=80=99d rather =
not close=E2=80=9D? What=C2=A0is Twitter going to do? Sue him? It is easy f=
or me, sitting here and looking at the contract, to say that Twitter would =
win that lawsuit and a court would order Musk to pay the money and close th=
e deal.=C2=A0I do think that![3] But actually making that happen=C2=A0requi=
res filing a lawsuit and going to court and asking a judge to make him pay =
billions of dollars to buy a company he doesn=E2=80=99t want. It requires h=
is banks to fund $13 billion of debt for a risky leveraged buyout whose whi=
msical buyer is no longer interested.Contractually this is all pretty butto=
ned-up, and I think a Delaware=C2=A0court would have a ton of sympathy for =
Twitter and none at all for Musk, who is acting in the most transparent and=
 smirking bad faith. But there is a lot that could still go wrong. Suing wo=
uld=C2=A0take time, and would cause bad publicity, and would create=C2=A0un=
certainty among employees and users and advertisers. Letting him walk, focu=
sing on=C2=A0the business, and taking the $1 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0or nego=
tiating a slightly higher breakup fee to save face =E2=80=94=C2=A0might be =
a better, though terrible, outcome for Twitter.As one merger arbitrageur pu=
t it to me, =E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re reading the contract, you=E2=80=99ve=
 lost.=C2=A0Lots of people reading the contract this morning.=E2=80=9D Sadl=
y I am one of them, and I do feel like I=E2=80=99ve lost.I think it is rele=
vant here that, in his efforts to buy Twitter so far,=C2=A0Elon Musk has vi=
olated all sorts of laws with no immediate repercussions. Both the  Securit=
ies and Exchange Commission and the  Federal Trade Commission are =E2=80=9C=
investigating=E2=80=9D the obvious facts that Musk did not make required se=
curities disclosures and antitrust filings as he was buying Twitter stock. =
The likely outcomes of these =E2=80=9Cinvestigations=E2=80=9D will be that =
the SEC and FTC will require Musk to pay small fines, likely considerably l=
ess than  the money he saved by ignoring the rules. And Musk=E2=80=99s earl=
ier scorched-earth battles with the SEC and other regulators suggest that t=
he agencies will have a hard time getting even those fines, that he will fi=
ght fiercely in court=C2=A0even when he transparently broke simple rules.  =
I wrote last month:There are rules, and he did not follow them, not as part=
 of an evil scheme but because he does not care. You could imagine the SEC =
getting mad about that and trying to impose consequences on him for violati=
ng the rules, but =E2=80=A6 what consequences? (The penalties for this stuf=
f are small, and it=E2=80=99s not like they will prevent him from buying Tw=
itter.) What=E2=80=99s the point? It will just be an exhausting slog of lit=
igation and mean tweets and he will emerge unchastened and richer than ever=
, and then he will try to stop the SEC lawyers from ever getting jobs in th=
e private sector. Why should they bother? What is the point of trying to en=
force the law against Elon Musk?Elon Musk has made it very clear that the r=
ule of law simply does not apply to him, and this has worked well for him. =
If he wants to ignore the merger agreement that he signed, he will. If you =
take him to court, he will put up a brutal fight and=C2=A0make things as un=
pleasant as possible for you. This puts his counterparties, like Twitter, i=
n a tough position. They have a contract. But so what?The third, most obvio=
us possibility is that Musk is going to make use of that uncertainty to ren=
egotiate the price. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d like to pay $42=C2=A0instead of $5=
4.20,=E2=80=9D he can say to Twitter=E2=80=99s board, =E2=80=9Cand if you s=
ay no I will walk away and you can sue me and, while you will be right, I w=
ill make your life horrible and might even win.=E2=80=9D Given the choice o=
f a long,=C2=A0miserable and uncertain lawsuit to force Musk to close at $5=
4.20, or a semi-amiable restriking=C2=A0of the deal at $42 (a number I just=
 made up, to be clear), Twitter=E2=80=99s board might take the $42.This wou=
ld be a hugely annoying outcome? For one thing, it would be a real failure =
by Twitter=E2=80=99s board. I have been  critical of the board=E2=80=99s pe=
rformance in this deal: Its quick decision to sell at the first price Musk =
offered, with no protections for Twitter=E2=80=99s culture or product, seem=
ed to me=C2=A0like the actions of a board that doesn=E2=80=99t really under=
stand or care about the company and a management with=C2=A0no good ideas. O=
n the other hand, since they struck the deal, tech stocks have collapsed, w=
hich makes the board=E2=80=99s decision to sell at $54.20 look smart. By lu=
ck or design, they got a great price for their shareholders at exactly the =
right time.If they give it up that will be really bad! Particularly because=
, as I just said, there is no=C2=A0good=C2=A0reason for them to give it up.=
 Musk signed a contract that requires him to buy Twitter for $54.20 per sha=
re, and there=E2=80=99s no reason to think a court would let him out of it.=
 It=E2=80=99s just that it would be fearsomely annoying to go to court agai=
nst him. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0hard to imagine Twitter's board playing hardball=
 against Musk, even if it really should.=C2=A0But mostly this would be an a=
nnoying outcome because it would reward Musk for not caring about contracts=
, for not caring about the rules, and for=C2=A0curating a reputation=C2=A0a=
s a guy who doesn=E2=80=99t care about rules. My thesis here is in essence:=
 Elon Musk is obligated to close his deal with Twitter at $54.20, but he=E2=
=80=99s obligated to follow lots of other rules too, and he doesn=E2=80=99t=
, and gets away with it, which means that if he ignores this obligation he=
=E2=80=99ll probably get away with it too. That is a terrible thesis! And y=
et.Anyway as of noon today there was no securities filing from Twitter or M=
usk about the deal supposedly being =E2=80=9Con hold,=E2=80=9D no press rel=
ease or tweet from Twitter investor relations or Chief Executive Officer Pa=
rag Agrawal, and no further clarification from Musk. The stock was trading =
a bit above=C2=A0$41, down almost 9% from yesterday=E2=80=99s close, almost=
 25% below the deal price. I feel for the lawyer who is working right now=
=C2=A0to file Musk=E2=80=99s tweet with the SEC: The filing will have to ex=
plain the tweet, and what is there to say?We have  discussed this before, b=
ut ordinarily in merger agreements there is a clause saying that the buyer =
and seller =E2=80=9Cshall consult with each other before issuing any press =
release or otherwise making any public statements with respect to=E2=80=9D =
the merger. Clear and consistent communication is really important; you don=
=E2=80=99t want anyone accidentally making statements that spook the market=
. Twitter=E2=80=99s agreement with Musk has that clause (Section 6.8), but =
it has an exception: =E2=80=9CNotwithstanding the foregoing, [Musk] shall b=
e permitted to issue Tweets about the Merger or the transactions contemplat=
ed hereby so long as such Tweets do not disparage the Company or any of its=
 Representatives.=E2=80=9DYou can see why Musk wanted that exception: His h=
ighest priority, the thing that he has fought over=C2=A0with the SEC, the=
=C2=A0reason he is buying Twitter, is his desire to tweet unsupervised. =E2=
=80=9CEveryone can tweet whatever they want=E2=80=9D has shoved aside=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Ccolonize=C2=A0Mars=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ctransition the world to su=
stainable energy=E2=80=9D as the thing Musk is interested in these days, so=
 of course his merger agreement lets him tweet whatever he wants without ru=
nning it by anyone. And you can see why Twitter gave him the exception: The=
y had to, plus I guess more tweeting is good for Twitter.But there=E2=80=99=
s a reason merger agreements usually say that the buyer and seller will con=
sult with each other before making significant announcements about the merg=
er! What a stupid mess this is.
