   =20
      Robinhood
   =20
 =20
Before, like, a month ago, it was pretty=C2=A0unusual for a rich guy to loo=
k at a public company, think =E2=80=9Chey I like that company,=E2=80=9D buy=
 a big stake in his personal account, and then say =E2=80=9Cyou know what I=
 like it so much I=E2=80=99m going to take it over.=E2=80=9D Companies boug=
ht companies, investment firms bought companies, rich founder-CEOs=C2=A0too=
k their own companies private, but for a rich founder-CEO of one big compan=
y to go buy=C2=A0another=C2=A0big company as a hobby would have been strang=
e. But then Musk did it and I guess it looked fun  and now:Sam Bankman-Frie=
d, the 30-year-old chief executive officer of crypto trading platform FTX, =
revealed late Thursday that he=E2=80=99d bought a 7.6% stake in [Robinhood =
Markets Inc.], which has lost 77% since its July public debut.The shares su=
rged 22% to $10.42 at 9:43 a.m. Friday in New York. They touched $11.70 in =
after-market trading Thursday.=C2=A0Bankman-Fried has said he intends to ho=
ld the stock as an investment and not to influence the company.Yeah I=E2=80=
=99ve  heard that before. Obviously Robinhood =E2=80=94=C2=A0a retail broke=
rage and, let=E2=80=99s face it, crypto trading platform =E2=80=94=C2=A0is =
a lot closer to Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s day job than Twitter is to Musk=E2=
=80=99s. (Or is it? Musk does spend a lot of time tweeting.) If he did buy =
Robinhood that would have a certain logic, though it would be weird for him=
 to do it in his personal account.=C2=A0
